{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583024/1921032701/0512.xml":{"full_text":"CUMMINS PLANS 1\nANOTHER STAB AT\nIowa Senator Insists, However,\nThat Intelligent Operation\nUnder Existing Law Will\nGet Hoped-for Result\nBy HUGH W. ROBERTS\nWufthinirtojL. Bureau The Age-Herald\n500 Davidson Building\n\u201cWashington. March 26. (Special.)\u2014\nSenator Cummins of Iowa, author of the\nCummins-Esch railroad act of 1920, who\nwill ask for a congressional investigation\ninto the entire railroad situation, makes\npublic, through the United States Cham\nber of Commerce today, statistics bear*\ning on railroad operations which, he ex\nplains, add to the confusion.\nIn other words, the senator doesn\u2019t\nknow what the matter is and what -the\nremedy should\\be. He admits that his\nlaw has not permitted the railroads to\nearn what they should earn, and has not\nbettered service or reduced rates. At\nthe same time, Senator Cummins declare*\nthat, in hfcp opinion, additional legisla\ntion is not necessary.\n\"An intelligent and efficient operation\nunder existing law,\" he said, \"would, in\nmy opinion, solve the question.\"\nThe statistics offered compare the ton\nnage moved by railroads in 1920 with\nyears immediately preceding, and the\npassenger traffic; also the cost of op\neration. and remuneration of labor, in\nthis regard, lie proceeds as follows:\nCOMPARATIVE TOTALS\n\"It is generally believed that during\nthe latter part of the year 1920 the vol\nume of^ traffic was materially less than\nfor corresponding periods in former\nyears, and, if this be true, It would tend\nto explain the decrease in net operating\nincome, for the cost of maintenance and\noperation does not diminsh in the exact\nproportion of a lessening traffia,\n\"The aggregate net ton miles carried\nfrom March 3, 1920, to December 31, 1920,\nwas 381,482,209,000. For the same period\nin 1919 the aggregate was 340,425,083,000.\nIt is, 1 assume, understood by every\nbody that the phrase, 'net ton-miles,\nmeans the number of tons of freight car\nried one mile. The number of ffasseng^t*\nmiles during the same time in 1920 was\n39,959,099,0^0, while for 1919 it was 39,582,\n264.000. Measured by this standard, the\nvolume of traffic upon all the railroads\nof the country was greater in 1920 than\nin 1919. In round numbers, figures for\nthe entire year 1918 are 360,000,000,000 and\nfor 1917, 350,000,000,000 with passenger\nmiles for those two years 35,000,000,000 and\n34.000. .000.000, respectively.\n\"Toward the latter part of the year,\nand continuing up to this time, there\nwas and still is a remarkable decrease\nin the number of cars of revenue freight\nloaded. The reports for January of this\nyear are not compiled, and the reports\nfor February have not been made, but\nI have advance information upon one\npoint, namely, the number of cars ol\nrevenue freight loaded. The following\ntable discloses that information and the\ncomparison with 1920:\n1920. 1921.\nJanuary 1 745,446 598,995\nJanuary 8 830,673 706,413\nJanuary 15 840,524 709,EL8\nJanuary 22 804,866 .03,llo\nJanuary 29 803,332 699,936\nFebruary 5 762,680 696,997\nFebruary 12 786,633 681,627\nFebruary 19 772,102 695,506\n\"Another indication of a condition\nwhich began in November. 1920, and\nwhich has progressed steadily up to the\npresent time, is a surplus of freight cars;\nthat is to say, the number of cars for\nwhich there is no present use. On De\ncember 21, 1920, the number of such cars\nwas 204,608. The number rose during\nJanuary, 1921, and at the close of that\nmonth was 324,186; and the last report,\non February 14, 1921, the number was\n290,550.\n\"These statistics very clearly show that\nwhile the volume of traffic for the last\n10 fcnonths of 1920, taken as a whole, was\ngreater than during the same period in\n1919, or indeed at any former similar pe\nroid, ^et, beginning as early as Novem\nber and proceeding rapidly to the pres\nent moment, there has been a tremendous\ndiminution in traffic. These statistics\naccord with our observation with respect\nto the decline in business during the lat\nter part of 1920 and the early part of\n1921.\nOPERATING COSTS\n\"I direct attention now to the operat\ning revenues and operating expenses\nfrom March 1, 1920, to December 31, 1920.\nThe operating revenues of all Class 1\nroads amounted to $5,299,664,464. Operat\ning expenses, including taxes and the\nadjustment of equipment and joint fa\ncility rates, amounted to $5,289,348,937,\nleaving a net operating income for these\n10 months of $10,306,517, and if we as\nsume that the remaining two months of\nthe year from March 1, 1920, to March 1,\n1921, show no better results, then, for the\nwhole period, the net operating income\nwill amount to no more than one-fif\nteenth of 1 per cent of the value of the\nrailroads as estimated by the interstate\ncommerce commission.\n\"It is interesting and instructive to\nknow that the net operating income for\nMarch, 1920, was $14,320,671. In April\nthere was a net deficit of $29,G04,417; ia\nMay of $13,455,871; in June of $16,284,900;\nin July of $10,427,989, and in AugUBt ol\n$165,227,617. The great deficit of August\nis probably accounted for by the back\ncompensation ordered paid to the em\nployes by the railroad labor board in\nJuly.\n\"In September, that being the first\nmonth under the increased rates which\nwere established by the interstate com\nmerce commission, there was a net op\nerating income of $75,310,311; in Obtober,\na net operating income of $86,455,387; in\nNovember, of $54,343,793; and in Decem\nber, of $10,225,583. The decreasing net in\ncome in November and December seems\ncoincident with the decreasing volume of\ntraffic which began in November and\nwhich is still in progress.\nCOST, MINUS TAXES\n\u201cIt may be helpful to Institute a com\nparison here and there. For January,\n1915, considering only Class 1 roads, rail\nway operating expenses were 1163,664,4oi!.\nIn December, 1916, these expenses were\n*184,510,067; in January, 1916, *183,702,959,\nand in December of that year, *209,615,966;\njn January, 1917, *215,496,356, and in De\n\u2022*e\"Kcr of that year *251,302,146; in Jan-,\nuafy, 1918, *271,621,592, and in December\nof that year, *396,408,865; in January, 1919,\n*360,465,81-5, and in December of that year,\n*414,615,756.\n\"The expenses I have just given do not\nIncludes taxes or the adjustment of\nequipment and Joint facility rents. In\nMarch, 1920, these expenses had risen to\n*421.713,184; in July, to *511,773,300; in Au\ngust,' to *678,728,682, and in December.\nU90, they had fallen to *523,206,889.\"\nSchools Are Improved\n\u2018Castleberry, March 20.\u2014(special.)\u2014\nEquipment representing an outlay of ap\nproximately *500 has been added to the\ndifferent departments of the Conecuh\nCounty High school during the past few\ndays. The departments benefited are'\nManual training, chemistry, physics, do\nmestic science, library and for general\nteaching work.\nStill Confiscated\nMontgomery, March 26.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nAn 80 gallon solid copper still was\nbrought to the capitol Saturday by\nthe state constabulary, having beer,\ncaptured in a barn four miles from\nMontgomery. A warrant has been\n\u25a0worn out against the person.charged\nvrlth the operation of ihp Still, but he\nlas not beer arrested.\nlanfied (Z la^crio:\nby^/fnti&Jfordan\nMOONSTONE\n(COLLINS)\nmru/rm\nlliJLUn\nv vaHrvy>/x n\nSergeant Cuff, at home on the job once again, removed hit disguise and the curly head of Godfrey-oh-s6-pure emerged.\nHigh on the forehead of the four\nhanded Moon God blossomed the love\nly moonstone, the forget-me-hot of the\nBrahmin priests, who guarded it day\nand night.\nThe moonstone was a huge yellow\ndiamond, with a curse and three Hin\ndoos tagged on to it, should anyone\ndare snitch it from its socket.\nBut dinky-dinky-dink! It tripped the\nvillains\u2014the conquering Monogols dis\nrespectfully operated on the Moon God.\nand the curse started working.\nAs each of the Vengeance Committee\nof Three pegged out with old age, their\ndescendants took up the sleuthing of\nthe moostone. After generations of\nmurders in different degrees, the moon\nstone at last opened its yellow eye on\na London fog. Colonel Jom Herncas\ntle, prominent in the storming of Ser\ningapatam, returned from India with\nthe sparkler. The colonel disgraced\nhimself with his family\u2014so, to get even\nwith them for handing him refrigerated\natmosphere, he died and left the moon\nstone to his niece, Rachael Verinder.\nTWO COUSINS COME A-WOOING\nRachael was a dainty frail, loved by\ntwo of her cousins, Franklin Blake and\nGodfrey Ablewhite. Franklin was a\nlady-killer, with a foreign education\nand a flock of outspoken debts; while\nGodfrey, a tend\u00abr begonia attired In\ncurly hair and gaiters, was chairman\nof all the Idle Women's Anti and Re\nligious clubs in London.\nThe moonstone was to be presented\non Rachael\u2019s birthday. There was a\ndinner party, and just beforehand God\nfrey led Rachael forth to the garden,\nand she shook her head.\n\"Devilish awkward,\" muttered God\nfrey, \"handing mo the huckleberry at\na time like this.\u2019\nAt dinner Rachael wore the diamond,\nand from the first the curse seemed to\nbe full of pep. All of the guests quar\nrelled. Even the sweet little physi\ncian, Dr. Candy, lost his temper when\nFranklin Blake insisted that though\nhe didn't sleep well, laudanum wouldn\u2019t\nhelp hjm sleep. The butler quietly re\nmoved the knives from the table.\nSuddenly from the terrace came the\nstrum of an Indian kettle-drum. The\nguests poured out to see three Hindoo\nJugglers performing tricks.\nThe next morning the diamond was\ngone!\nNext in the horoscope came the po\nlice. The locals gummed things up for\nfair, so Sergeant Cuff, a special from\nLondon, was sent for. The first thing\nthat he glued his eagle eye on was a\nsplotch of smeared paint on Rachael's\nsitting room door.\nWho got the diamond?\nGODFREY OFFERS\nTO SHOW EVERYTHING\nThere was the lily pure Godfrey, kist\nby the morning dew, anxious to show\nhis wardrobe against telltale paint\nsmears. Franklin Blake, right-hand\nman to Sergeant Cuff, was eager to do\nanything to help locate the unlucky\nstone. Rachael alone refused to have\nher lingerie handled by a policeman.\nThen. too. there was a second house\nmaid, 'Rosanna Spearman, who hailed\nfrom a reformatory, who kept dodging\naround like a cat shot with tacks. The\nsergeant gave up the job.\nRachael slipped Franklin a few harsh\nv/oras and he left for the continent;.\nGodfrey returned to lecture to his ladies'\nclub in London. Rachael being ill, Dr.\nCandy was. sent for, but the doctor him\nself was very ill with brain fever and\ncouldn\u2019t come. Rosanna Spearman took\na dive in a bod of quicksand and re\nfused to leave a forwarding address.\nRachael\u2019s mother took Rachael to Lon\ndon.\nOne day a few weeks after, Mr. Sep\ntimus Luker, a three-ball baron, with a\nnon-inquiring nature, made a deposit of\na valuable package at the bank. Almost\nsimultaneously both Mr. Luker and God\nfrey Ablewhite were jiu-jitsued and raf\nfled by three dusky gentlemen from\nIndia.\nGodfrey slipped Rachael another chance\nto call him her own, and to his surprise\nshe took it.\nFranklin Blake\u2019s father died, and he\nreturned to England. He went to call\non Rachael, but she wouldn\u2019t see him.\nHe went back to the country home to\ntry his luck once again at locating the\nmoonstone, thinking maybe that had\nsomething to do with Rachael\u2019s nasty\ndisposition. He was handed a note writ\nten by Rosanna Spearman just before\nshe kicked the bucket, telling him to\ndig up a certain spot and he would find\nthe shimmy shirt with the paint spot on\nit that Sergeant Cuff had been sleuth\ning for. He dug, he found, he beheld\u2014\nhis own night shirt! Smeared with\npaint. (Moral, he should have worn\npajamas).\nHe managed to see Rachael, and she\ncried indignantly:\n\u201cYou poor hungry-eyed, long-eared,\ncieDt-naaen cootie: I saw you when you\ncopped them jewel. Then to try to kid\nme that way!\u201d\nTHE HOP-FEST IS RE-ENACTED\nBack to the woods went Franklin. He\nmet a snowbird, Dr. Jennings, assistant\nto Dr. Candy, who told him that Dr.\nCandy had been off his ker-zip since\nRachael\u2019s dinner, and had been talking\nin his sleep about Dr. Jennings coped\nup on morphine, and made Franklin\nsniff a little more snow. With Rachael\nand plenty of other witnesses, Franklin\nperformed a stunning Dady Macbeth,\nheading straight for the place where the\nmoonstone had been. But he didn\u2019t show\nthem what he did with the moonstone.\nIt didn\u2019t matter much.. Shortly after,\na sailor who received a package from\nMr Septimus Duker was smothered with\na pillow and three Indians left England\nforever. Sergeant Cuff, at home on the\njob once again, removed his disguise and\nthe curley head of Godfrey-oh-so-pure\nemerged. It turned out that Franklin,\non his morphine bat, had tossed the\nstone to Godfrey, who said, \u2018\u2018Thank\nyou,\u201d and hocked it to Mr. Luker.\nNeedless to add, Rachael and Franklin\nwere married.\nBack in India the Moon God, resplend\nent once more with the diamond in his\nbean, wore a snicker on his face that\nseemed to say:\n\u201dT guess that\u2019ll settle their hash for a\nwhile! I\u2019ve been eight centuries getting\neven, but time is nothing in my younfe\nlife. I\u2019m a double-dyed. tack-eating,\nfour-handed tough guy! Better lay off\nmy moonstone, I\u2019ll say!\u201d\nCHANGE OF PLANS\nIndicated Decision on Alimony\nand Counsel Fees Will\nBe Delayed\nBy Associated Press\nWhite Plains, N. Y\u201e March 26.\u2014When\nand where public access will be given\npapers presented by both sides In the\ndivorce action of James A. Stillman,\npresident of the National City bank\nof New York, against the former \"Flfl\"\nPotter, became more beclouded today\nwhen a shift in Supreme Court Jus\ntice Morschauser's plans for filing his\ndecision on alimony and counsel fees\nwas announced.\nCharles E. Long of counsel for Mr.\nStillman said the justice would give\nthe papers and decision to the court\nclerk here with instructions to file\nthem in Putnam covjnty. Yesterday it\nwas announced at Yonkers that the\ndocuments would be filed and made\npublic here, probably early next week,\nand later transmitted to Putnam coun\nty, where the action was begun.\nIndications are, therefore, that the\ndecision will be made public in Carmel,\nthe Putnam county seat, instead of\nW'hite Plains, and that Justice Mor\nschauser will not render a decision be\nfore the end of next week, instead of\nMonday.\nOLD PAXNE-ALDRICH\nTARIFF AGREED UPON\nIN FRAMING NEW BILL\nBy Associated Press\nWashington, March 26.\u2014The old Payne\nAldrich tariff duty on grease wool of 11\ncents a pound has been agreed upon by\nthe House subcommittee framing the\npermanent tariff measure to be intro\nduced at the extra session. Members said\ntoday the wool schedule probably would\nbe adopted by the full committee with\nout material change.\nTaking grease wool as the basis, the\nrate on washed would be 22 cents and on\nscoured 33 cents. In the emergency tar\niff the grease wool duty is 16 cents.\nBy accepting these figures the com\nmittee virtually revived schedule K., long\nfought over in Congress. Chairman Ford\nney of the ways and means, is chair\nman of the sub committee on wool, other\nmembers being Watson, Pennsylvania;\nBecharach, New Jersey; all republicans.\nMr. Fordney told republicans today\nthat tariff revision would have clear\nright of way in the House. The com\nmlttee bill for revision of -the internal\nrevenue taxes will not be introduced, he\nsaid, until both the emergency tariff\nand the general revision bills have been\npassed.\nRepresentatives Fordney conferred with\nChairman Penrose of the Senate fi\nnance committee, and is understood to\nhave been urged to modify his plans for\nprocedure with the internal tax legisla\ntion.\nAs near simultaneous consideration of\nthe tariff and tax bills as possible is ad\nvocated by several Influential republican\nsenators.\nBurke Seeks Damages\nBy Associated Press\nChicago, March 26. -Damages of Mffi.OUO\nwere sought in a libel suit begun today\nin circuit court by John Burke,\"*for\nmerly treasurer of the United States and\nat one time governor of North Dakota;\nand Louts M. Kardos against R. H.\nMcMaster, a local broker. The charges\nwere not specified In the praecipe, but\nPhillip R. Davis, attorney,for Burke and\nKardos, who have a brokerage concern\nhere, said they had been given McMas\nter's business some time ago when the\nlatter went out of business. McMaster.\nDavis said, had reopened his offices and\nin trying to regain the business given\nBurke and Kardos, had called their con\ncern a bucket shop.\"\n\nSELMA WILL PROVIDE\nTWO THOUSAND PIES\nFOR\u201cROTE\"APPROVAL\nSelma, March 20.\u2014< Special.)\u2014The\npie counter at Washington will be\nno more popular place the coming\nweek than that in the Tutwiler ho\ntel, from which Miss Charlene MU- J\nler and wltei of Selma Rotarian*\nwill dispense small sweet potato\nplea and glasses of rich sweet milk,\nproducts of Dallas county and\nSelma.\nThe pies, 2,000 of them, are made\nfrom sugar-cured sweet potatoes\nfrom the Selma sweet potato cur\ning house, and **e the best ever.\nThe aweet milk is from the two\nSelma creameries, and Is a fitting\nside partner for the pie.\nJ. Percy Day, in charge of the\nSelma Rotary club\u2019s exhibit at the\nFourth district convention, has sent\n200 tickets to brokers and grocery\nmen of Birmingham entitling them\nto a \u201cfree lunch\u201d at the pie counter.\nFRENCHARE PLEASED\nU. S. Rejection of Red Proposals Re\nceived With Satisfaction\nDr Aiwentled Pre\nParis, March 26.\u2014Press dispatches\ntelling of the, rejection by the Amer\nican Secretary of State, Charles E,\nHuges, of the' Russian soviet trade\nproposals were received with satisfac\ntion in official circles here today.\nWhile none Of the officials would\npermit himself to be quoted, all were\nundisguisedly pleased that the United\nStates had seen fit to reject Lenlne\u2019a\nplea for recognition; the French in^.\nterpreting the American attitude as a\ncertain amount of aupport of the\nFrench viewpoint regarding the soviet\nrepublic.\nComing as it does after England\u2019s\ntrade agreement with the soviets, the\nofficials believe the American refusal\nmere than counteracts any strength\nthe bolsheviki may have gained\nthrough their successful negotiations\nwith Great Britain. The news was re\nceived here too late for comment by\nthe afternoon newspapers.\nLITVINOFF T0*BE NEW\nSOVIET ENVOY TO U. S.\nBy Associated Pre\nHelsingfors, March 2*.\u2014Maxim Lit\nvinoff, chief of the Russian soviet\nlegations abroad, it ia reported from\nReval, has been selected to succeed\nLudwig Martens as Russian soviet\nenvoy in the United States.\nMartens arrived in Moscow last\nmonth from the United States, from\nwhich country he was ordered de\nported by the Washington government.\nStorm Exaggerated\nHuntsville, March 2S.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Wire\ncommunication was re-established today\nwith the New Hope region, where sev\neral persons were reported killed In a\ncyclone yesterday. No casualties oc\ncurred, although considerable damage\nwas done by wind and hall.\nFuneral'services\nAnniston, March 2fl.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Funeral\nservices for Miss Madeline Tidwell,\nwhose death occurred at the family home\non Stephens Hill, north of the city,\nThursday night, were held from the resi\ndence Saturday at U o\u2019clock'. Rev. Noah\nStephen* in charge The body was in\nterred in the family lot at Pino Grove.\nBachelors Alls Guests\nAnniston, March 2fi.\u2014(Special.)\u20141The\nmembers of the Anniston Bachelors' club,\neach member accompanied by hie best\ngirl, attended a picture show party last\nnight as the guest of Maj. I. C. Hollo\nway, resident manager of the Savoy\ntheatre. 7\n\nOnly Part of Those Engaged\nDuring War Period Lose\nPlaces in Peace Times\nBy Associated Press\nChicago, March 26. Only part\nof the women engaged in industry\nduring the war period have lost their\nplaces through the return of men from\nthe war and the lack of employment,\nMiss Mary Anderson, director of the\nwomen\u2019s bureau of the United States\ndepartment of labor, reports.\n\"Statements to the bureau from hun\ndreds of industry heads who \u201c\u2018Employea\nonly women during the war show they\nhave retained their female heiy, while\nothers state they have replaced their\nwomen with male workers,\" #Miss Ander\nson said. \"Because of the volume of un\nemployment throughout the country to\nday no accurate figures as to the num\nber of women employed in industries at\npresent as compared with the war period\nare obtainable.\n*1 believe that when figures of the\n1920 census are available, they will show\nmore than 12,000,000 women In gainful oc\ncupation. The census, however, will not\nset forth the present situation because\nunemployment has increased by leaps\nand bounds since it was taken. Women\nwon the admiration of employers during\nthe war period by their ability to fill in\non men\u2019s jobs. Take, for instance, lathe\noperators. Thousands of women became\nvery efficient *ud still retain their places\nbeside men operators. The war gavo\nAmerican women a new opportunity in in\ndustry and they grasped it.\"\nThere are two factors needed to in\nsure women their place in industry, Miss\nAnderson said. Protective legislation for\nthe eight-hour day is badly needed, sne\ndeclared, and added that the women must\n\"organize within the next few\u2014years.\nWith the return of prosperity, indus\ntries will clamor for women worKers\nin the opinion of Miss Mary E. McDowell\nof the University of Chicago Settlement\nhouse, who is chairman of the women\nin industry committee of the National\nLeague of Women Voters.\n0 N0L PROS CASES\nOF THREE OR MORE.\nACCUSED OF THEFTS\nMacon, Ga., March 2\u00ab.\u2014Three and\nposibly five cases of the 53 persons\naccused of conspiracy to steal express\nshipments from the United States\ngovernment will be nol prossed Mon\nday morning, it was announced today\nby Assistant District Attorney E.\nClem Powers.\nMr. Powers said that he would com\nplcte the government\u2019s case in' one\nhour Monday morning. Wallace Mil\nler, who represents 31 of the defend\nants, stated that he would call 100\nwitnesses and predicted that the pr$\nsentation of the defense would require\none month.\nClean-Up Plan Complete\nMeridian, Miss., March 28.\u2014(Special.)\nPlans ha.ve been about completed for\ngiving Meridian a thorough clean-tuL\nall\nAll citizens are urged to co-opera?\nWith the city authorities in the wo$k\nof making the city apotless and thor\noughly sanitary during the coming\nwarm season.\nChild, 7, Is Buried\nAnniston, March 26.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Curry\nEugene McKelroy, seven years of a^e,\nwho died Friday night at the home ot\nhis grandparents, Mr. and Mrs. Rtchard\nMcKelroy. |\u00abras buried at Edgemont\ncemetery Saturday afternoon following\nservices at the home by Rev. Leon it.'\nLatimer.\nN\nThese Women Employes\nObject to Negro Chief\nBy HUGH W. ROBERTS\n(TMhlBiton Bureau The Ago-Herald,\n500 Davidson Building.\nWashington, March 2d.\u2014(Spe\ncial.)\u2014The women employe* of the\noffice of the register of the treas\nury are circulating a petition in\nwhich they will urge the secretary\nto refrain from appointing a negro\nto the office of register.\nThere Is current a report that a\nnegro, Henry Lincoln Johnson of\nGeorgia, will be appointed regis\nter. The petition is not signed by\nmale employes because they are not\nInvited to sign. The women pre\nparing to petition are from all sec\ntions of the country and affiliate\nwith both major political parties.\nHARDING SEEKS ADVICE\nOF DAWES IN REGARD TO\nSOLDIER BONUS POLICY\nBjr Associated Ftps#\nWashington, March 36.\u2014To ask for ad\nvice regarding an administration policy\ntoward soldier compensation and related\nsubjects. President Harding today called\nto Washington Charles Q. Dawes of \u00aehi\ncago, who served as a brigadier genera!\nir. France and who at one time was\nprominently under consideration for Sec\nretary of the Treasury in the Harding\ncabinet.\nMr, Dawes would not Indicate the rec\nommendation he took to the White House\nnor forecast what the President's deci\nslop might be. He will remain here over\nSunday and will go to dinner at the\nWhite House tomorrow with F. W. Gal\nbraith of-Cleveland, commander in chief\nof the American Legion; Thomas, W.\nMiller, alien property custodian, and\nAssistant Secretary Roosevelt of the\nnavy department, all of whom have been\nactive In the work of the legion since\nits organization It is assumed that the\nPresident will take advantage of the op\nportunity for a general discussion of the\nsoldier relief problem.\nHAYS PROMISES TO\nGIVE PREFERENCE TO\nFORMER SERVICE MEN\nBy Associated Press\nWashington, March 26.\u2014iPromise that\nhe would observe the spirit as well a\u00bb\nthe letter of the law giving prefer\nence to former service men in the\npostal service was given by Postmas\nter General Hays today to a commit\ntee of the American Legloil.\nThe legion committee, consisting of\nTheodore Roosevelt, assistant secretary\nof the navy; Thomas W. Miller, alien\nproperty cuetodian, and D. John Mar\nkey of Frederick, Md., laid before the\nPostmaster General several specific\ncases' of discrimination against former\nservice men. Mr. Hays promised t^\nhave the oases investigated immedi\nately and assured the committee he\nwas in full sympathy with the law\ndirecting officials of the postal serv\nice to consider time spent by employes\nin the military service on their postal\nrecord. v\nMINIMUM FEE STOPS\nState Board Issues Order to Alabama\nWater Company\nMontgomery, March 26.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nThe Alabama Water company, which\nsupplies water to citizens of Albany\nand Decatur, must discontinue tr.e\ncollection of a minimum charge against\neach family using an apartment house.\nIn the future only one minimum charge\nmay be collected, and any excess may\nbe charged under the rules for excess\nwater, under a decision of the public\nservice commission Saturday. John B.\nWeakley, attorney or the company,\nold the commission early In the week\nthat the dlscontlnuonce of the mini\nmum charge against each family\nwould mean a loss in revenue of more\nthan 92,00V a year.\nSherman Lost More Men On\nHistoric \u201cMarch to the Sea\u201d\nThan in the Confederate Army\nBy W. H. PARTRIDGE,\nGoodwater, Ala.\nGoodwater, March 26.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nThe writer was a member of Co. H.,\nBell\u2019* Battalion, and was mustered into\nservice at Montgomery about March\n12, 1862. In June. 1862, at Corinth,\nMiss., Bell's Battalion and other bat\ntalions were united and formed the\nEighth Confederate cavalry and served\nin this organisation during the re\nmainder of the war under Gen. Joe\nWheeler.\nThis regiment possibly saw as much\nservice as any other regiment in the\nwestern army. We left Corinth in\nJune, 1862, and crossed the Warrior\nriver, fording the same, north of Bir\nmingham, on to Gadsdep, from Gadsden\nto Blue Mountain, on to Rome, Chat\ntanooga and on to Perryville, Ky.,\nwhere we were engaged in that bloody\nbattle, routing the enemy. We then\nmarched to Camp Dick Robinson. At\nthis point the Tanakees began to press\nus and we were forced to retreat to\nCumberland Gap, and from there back\nto Murphreesboro, Tenn., where the\nwestern army under General Bragg,\nand the northern army under General\nThomas fought the battle of Mur\nphreesboro or Stone River, lasting two\ndays, being just about Christmas, 1862.\nThis was a fierce and awful battle,\neach army losing thousands of men.\nYANKS REINFORCED\nThe northern army brought up heavy\nreinforcements and the Confederate\narmy was forced to fall back qn Chat\ntanooga and Chickamauga, and In Sep\ntember, 1863, at Chickamauga, Ga., the\nnorthern army attacked our army with\nmuch larger army than ours, well\nequipped with artillery and rifles and\nample munitions, and for two days the\narmies were in death grapple, and on\nthe third day of the battle the Yankees\nwere routed and foiled to retire on\nChattanooga. Had if not been for the\ngeneralship of General Thomas of the\nnorthern army, the entire enemy would\nhave b'wn destroyed or utterly routed,\nbut as it was, the enemy succeeded in\nretiring with most of its artillery.\nBragg's army followed up the enemy,\nlaying siege to Chattanooga, taking\nup positions on Lookout Mountain and\nMissionary Ridge. Here the northern\narmy was again heavily reinforced and\nattacked our forces and succeeded in\nforcing us to retire from Chattanooga\ntowards Dalton, Resaca and finally\nback to Atlanta, Ga., and at the last\nplace the Batle of Atlanta was fought\nIn July, 1*64. General Sherman was\nplaced in command of the northern\narmy at Chattanooga, and on his of\nfensive to Atlanta he lost more men\nthan was in our army.\nThe battle of Atlanta was a bloody\nfight, lasting two days. Here the Con\nfederate army retired and in a move\noutflanked the enemy, Gen. Joe John\nston was in tmmmand of the Confed\nerate army frbna Chattanooga to At\nlanta. Here Gesreral Hood suceeded\nGeneral Johnston. Prom Atlanta Gen\neral Hood with about 40,000 men\nmarched back t\u00bb Farnklin, Tenn.,\nwhere the battle of Franklin was\nfought, and while it lasted only threo\nhours, the carnage was fearfful and\nrouted the enemy. Gen. Pat Cleburne\nwas killed in this fight, the writer\nseeing him after his death on the field\nof battle. General Cleburne was a\nbrave and courageous soldier and an\nable leader.\nNORTHERN RESOURCES\nThe Yankee army retreated to Nash\nville and General Hood followed it. On\nthe outskirts of the city we were at\ntacked by the enemy and It is said that\nnegro troops of the enemy pierced our\nlines and we were forced to retreat\nfrom Nashville. We had been fighting\ncontinuously for over a year or on the\nmarch, an'd our numbers had been\ngreatly reduced, and after the battle\nof Nashville, we were taken to Vir\nginia, and soon thereafter the sur\nrender took place.\nAs an old soldier of the Dost Cause,\nand realizing that our time here at\nbest can be only a few years, we have\nwritten this article for the informa\ntion of those interested in military op\nerations, especially to those who fought\nin the Eighth Confederate cavalry\nand their descendants. We reflect\nnow, in closing, on that old war song,\nin part as follows:\n\u201cWhen our rights were threatened.\nThe cry went near and far:\nThree cheers for the bonny blue flag,\nThat bears a single star.\u201d\nCHANT WILL B\u00a3\nSUNG AT FUNERAL\n_\nAmong Most Beautiful and Im\npressive Compositions Ever\nWritten for Gregorian\nChoir\nBy Associated Press\nBaltimore, March 26.\u2014At the funeral\nservices for Cardinal Gibbons next\nThursday in the Cathedral there will be\nsung music heard before only at thsi\nfunerals of sovereign rulers of the Cath\nolic church in the sistine chapel in\nRome. The manuscript never before has\nleft the Vatican.\nJust before the body is laid to rest m\nthe crypt beneath the Cathedral altar\nand the distinguished assemblage stands\nwith bowed heads, this solemn Grego\nrian chant will he sung.\nThis music, which was prepared es\npecially for funeral services of popes, Is\narffong the most beautiful and impressive\ncompositions ever written for a Grego\nrian choir. It will be sung by the Gre\ngorian Choral society of St. Marys sem\ninary.\nA manuscript copy of the music, be\nlieved to be the first which has ever\nfound its way out of the Vatican, ar\nrived in Baltimore early last week\nSome time ago, when the Cardinal was\nvery ill, the subject of Gregorian music,\nwhich the late prelate loved, was being\ndiscussed with the apostolic delegate in\nWashington.\nIS ORDERED SENT\nThen came the suggestion that Rome\nbe asked if a copy of the papal funeral\nmusic could be sent to Baltimore in tho\nevent of the Cardinal's death, as a\nspecial recognition from Rome of the\nAmerican prelate's services to tho\nchurch. This request was transmitted at\nthe time and Pope Benedict ordered the\nauthorities of the pontifical chapel, of\nwhom the music is the exclusive prop\nerty. to have a manuscript copy made\nand sent to the Very Rev. E. R. Dyer,\npresident of St. Marys seminary, and\npresident of the Society of St. Gregory\nin America.\nWith the arrival of the music just be\nfore the Cardinal\u2019s death, a small group\nof the late prelate\u2019s personal friends\nwere asked to finance the printing of the\nmusic for the choir.\nThe Cardinal's body will rest for the\nlast time tomorrow night on his own bed\nin his room at the archepiscopal res\nidence watched over by special guards of\nChristian Brothera Early Monday morn\ning it will be removed, without special\nceremony, to the cathedral, where it\nwill lie in state until the funeral Thurs\nday.\nThe body will be placed in position just\noutside the sanctuary at the head of the\ncentral aisle. Just before the first re\nquiem mass at 10 o\u2019clock, which will be\nfor children of the archdiocese.\nThe guard of honor, consisting of 876\nmen, will be maintained from 8 a. m.\nMonday until 9 a. m. Thursday. It will\nbe changed hourly, and will consist of\n12 men at a time, one from each of 12\nbig Catholic laymen's organixationa\nBishop Owen B. Corrygan was con\nfirmed as administrator of archdiocese\nby Monsignor John Bonxana, apostolic\ndelegate to the United States, today and\nimmediately assumed charge of the cler\nical affairs.\nInquiries Continue\nMontgomery, March 26.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nWestern states showed their interest\nin the agriculture future of Alabams\nthis week by requesting information\nabout soils, climate and general agri\ncultural conditions of the bureau of\nmarkets and immigration of the state\ndepartment of agriculture. The weekly\nsummary made public Saturday show\ned the following Inquiries during the\nweek from Missouri, Colorado and\nother states.\nMAN WHO KILLED\nSTEP-SON CONVICTED\nOllie Barbaree, Jury fifties Most\nServe 25 Years\u2014Two\nCourts In Session\nTuscaloosa, March 26.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Oms\nBarbaree was convicted In circuit court\nhere this afternoon of manslaughter and\nwas sentenced to the penitentiary for 25\nyears. Barbaree is charged -with killing\nJim Savage, his stepson. The case has\nbeer, on trial for two days.\nAn unusual feat for the Tuscaloosa cir\ncuit court was the trying of two flrst\ndegree murder cases at the same hour to\nday. Washington Moody was selected as\ntemporary judge In the Wheat murder\ncase, and S. E. Moore and T. B. Ward\nacted as special prosecutors, while Judge\nH. B. Foster and Solicitor Edgar Clark\nson and another Jury were trying Bar\nbaree.\nWheat is a negro and was acquitted.\nSON SLAYS FATHER AND\nSURRENDERS TO SHERIFF\nClanton, March 26.\u2014Albert Gore was\nshot and killed yesterday by his 16\nyear-old son, Arthur Gore, near Lock\n12 on the Coosa river, in Coosa county,\naccording to reports received here to\nday.\nGore, the reports say, was pursuing\nIlls son with an ax. The youth secured\na rifle and fired to defend himself,\nit was stated. After shooting his\nfather, the boy telephoned county\nauthorities here and surrendered later\nto the sheriff.\nStole Mole, Alleged\nMeridian. Miss., March 26.\u2014Special.)\nHenry Walker, negro, is being held by\nthe authorities here as a suspect in\nconnection with the theft of a mule\nfrom J. D. Hunnlcutt of Meehan, Miss.*\nPerpetuate The\nMemory Of Your\nLoved Ones\nby seeing to it that their lash\nlong rest is in a hallowed, se\ncluded spot never encroached\nupon in any way, or suffered\nto deteriorate for lack of\nthoughtful attention.\nSuch a place is Elmwood, the\nM/ode 1 Memorial Park, pro\ntected by our perpetual main\ntenance fund for all time to\ncome.\nQur booklet will show you-the\nbeauties of this sacred spot and\ntell about our easy payment\nplan.\nElmwood Cemetery\nC/' Corporation cv\nAve. F and Montevallo Road\nPhone W. End 745\nLUMBER\nIt lui been demonstrated beyond i doubt, lumber of\nstandard quality, finished officiant, is the secret to a\nbeautiful and substantial homo.\nOur many successful years in this business has en\nabled us to supply you tho standard quality, service and\nat low prices.\nWhich means economy to you. Estimates promptly\nfurnished.\nJenkins Lumber Co.\nYard, Mill, Office, 19th St. and 10th Are.,' North*\nPhone 7486-7487","height":"28136","width":"19772"}}
